 did she cope with the sudden death of her husband ‚Ä¢ scroll down for an exclusive extract from sandberg‚Äôs new book share on facebook share on twitter share via email view more sharing options share on linkedin share on pinterest share on google share on whatsapp share on messenger close decca aitkenhead sunday  april  ¬†edt last modified on sunday  april  ¬†edt sheryl sandberg‚Äôs last words to her husband like all last words assumed a haunting poignancy ‚Äúi‚Äôm falling asleep‚Äù she told him oblivious to the imminence of tragedy and curled up on a cushion for a nap it was friday  may  she and dave goldberg  had left their two children at home with her parents in northern california and flown down to mexico for a weekend break to celebrate a friend‚Äôs th birthday they were silicon valley royalty‚Äôs power couple he the ceo of a tech company worth more than bn she the chief operating officer of facebook and author of global bestseller lean in a feminist call to arms for working women to emulate the selfbelief and ambition of men sandberg had featured on forbes‚Äô list of the most powerful women on the planet served as chief of staff to the treasury secretary in bill clinton‚Äôs government been widely tipped as a future member of a hillary clinton cabinet and earned a personal fortune well in excess of bn at  she was mother to a yearold son and sevenyearold daughter weekends away were rare and precious no wonder she was tired she fell asleep that afternoon a happily married wife and woke up an hour later a widow when sandberg didn‚Äôt see her husband she at first thought nothing of it and joined her friends for a swim she took a shower spoke to their son on the phone and dressed for dinner it was only when she rejoined the group on the beach and realised no one had seen goldberg for hours that panic set in racing to the resort gym she found him lying on his back his face blue a pool of blood around his head she performed frantic cpr an ambulance rushed him to hospital but it was too late he had suffered a fatal heart attack sandberg flew home that evening to tell her children their father had died the news of sandberg‚Äôs loss made global headlines but held a particular resonance for my family i knew what it was to fly away a happy couple and come home with a coffin for our own beach holiday had shattered into tragedy  months earlier when my partner had drowned as a member of what sandberg calls ‚Äúthis club of ours no one ever wants to join‚Äù i wasn‚Äôt surprised that she went back to work  days later ‚Äì when every room in your house is haunted by memories the longing for refuge is overwhelming nor was i surprised by the problem she was floored to find waiting for her at the office ‚Äúyou know we were facebook we were very open we sit at open desks and we share openly‚Äù she tells me as we talk at facebook hq in menlo park in northern california sandberg doesn‚Äôt even have her own office at work but sits among her colleagues in a vast openplan space ‚Äúit‚Äôs part of who we are we share but everyone looked at me like i was a ghost no one would talk to me‚Äù she confided in her boss mark zuckerberg ‚Äúall my relationships are gone and no one will talk to me‚Äù he told her ‚Äúthey want to they just don‚Äôt know what to say‚Äù in jewish tradition the mourning period for a spouse lasts for  days as it drew to a close sandberg took a risk so out of character that even now she seems faintly amazed by herself she wrote an unfiltered account of her griefstricken month and posted it publicly on facebook ‚Äúthe night before i thought this is a terrible idea this is too personal too raw there‚Äôs no way i‚Äôm posting this‚Äù but when she woke the next morning ‚Äúi was like this is supposed to be the end of mourning i could not feel less like the end of mourning this is horrible and i said you know it‚Äôs not going to get worse and i just hit post and it broke open the dam‚Äù sandberg‚Äôs post has attracted more than  comments to date strangers all over the world flooded her facebook page with tales of their own tragedies and heartbreaks ‚Äúand you know‚Äù she says ‚Äúafter that i didn‚Äôt feel alone any more‚Äù facebook twitter pinterest with husband dave goldberg in  four years before his sudden death photograph julie jacobsonap if something as simple as sharing stories could have such a radical impact on her grief sandberg wondered what else might why is it that some people never recover from loss while others emerge with greater resilience to lead more meaningful lives working with a psychologist adam grant sandberg studied the research of behavioural scientists neurologists and psychologists for techniques empirically proven to build resilience to her amazement she discovered that by applying them all she wouldn‚Äôt just recover but could actually achieve ‚Äúposttraumatic growth‚Äù option b sandberg and grant‚Äôs book is part personal memoir and part practical manual for how to withstand catastrophe and grow from adversity she even claims it can deliver ‚Äúpretraumatic growth‚Äù for readers yet to suffer loss themselves who fortify themselves with the lessons she has learned had i not yet read the book this might sound to me like the laughable nonsense of california selfhelp but option b named after the idea that if your option a is taken away you have to ‚Äúkick the shit out of option b‚Äù is the single wisest book about grief i have ever found and so useful that i only wish it had been in print three years ago when i was widowed i would have stuck pages to my fridge and sent it to relatives who wanted to help but didn‚Äôt know how so cleared off rather than get it wrong all we‚Äôd needed was a book spelling out how to help when i was too broken to explain i have tried to think of anyone who would not find option b invaluable at some point in their life and i can‚Äôt  facebook hq lies  miles south of san francisco on a forgettable stretch of industrial estate flanked by a freeway whoever designed it went to some lengths to perfect an aggressively glamourfree aesthetic the grey metal building is a quarter of a mile long stands on top of a nineacre car park and is accessed by squat silver buildings which look uncannily like the entrance lobbies found in ikea car parks the resemblance to ikea does not end there each lobby is furnished by a reception that appears to have been knocked together in a hurry out of makeshift plywood but on closer inspection turns out to be permanent stairs lead up to the first floor where openplan office space stretches as far as the eye can see and accommodates  staff the interior looks halffinished ‚Äì concrete floors no ceiling to conceal the industrial tangle of electrical cables and ventilation flues overhead ‚Äì but facebook moved in two years ago so this must be how it‚Äôs meant to look rows of identical white desks are punctuated by columns identified by numbers like an ikea warehouse presumably to help staff find their way back facebook calls its hq a campus and it‚Äôs easy to see why as i don‚Äôt spot anyone over  and everybody is dressed like an undergraduate sandberg‚Äôs desk is somewhere near the middle and looks like everyone else‚Äôs we will meet in a big glass box one of two meeting rooms and the only enclosed spaces i see i was not shocked by the anger not shocked by the sadness but the selfconfidence blow completely surprised me but no amount of gratuitous architectural austerity can distract from the power and wealth of this organisation for most of which its coo is almost singlehandedly responsible sandberg joined from google in  and turned facebook from a popular tech startup that didn‚Äôt make money into one of the wealthiest companies on the planet she comes to meet me straight after the photoshoot looking like an italian screen siren all tiny birdlike limbs and big luxurious hair and is shockingly beautiful to my surprise she throws her arms around me and showers me in flattery ‚Äúi‚Äôm so glad you‚Äôre doing this interview‚Äù she tells me fixing a luminescent gaze ‚Äúbecause you get it‚Äù in the early months after goldberg‚Äôs death sandberg says she made the three classic mistakes ‚Äì ‚Äúthe three ps ‚Äì personalisation pervasiveness and permanence‚Äù she blamed herself for his death ‚Äúespecially because the early reports which were false said he died by falling off an exercise machine so i absolutely thought that if i had looked for him sooner he would be alive a friend would say to me ‚Äòyou didn‚Äôt leave a threeyearold alone in a gym‚Äô but i felt hugely guilty‚Äù when the autopsy revealed undiagnosed coronary artery disease ‚Äúi spent months thinking i should have known that i felt hugely guilty you blame yourself endlessly then one day adam grant said ‚Äòif you do not recover your kids cannot recover that is it you must‚Äô so that really snapped me out of it i was like ok this isn‚Äôt my fault i stopped taking it personally ‚Äúthen the pervasiveness you don‚Äôt want to feel that anything‚Äôs good as in ‚Äòcan i feel ok about work how can i feel ok‚Äô right and then the permanence and that for me was the hardest it felt in the depths of grief that i would always feel sad it would always feel that bad and the sadness is still here i still miss him every day but it does not feel like it did in the beginning when you can‚Äôt breathe that‚Äôs why i shared so openly about the pain and the grief because i think the only way people are going to think it gets better is if they know you feel what they were feeling‚Äù sandberg writes about the moment she had to break the news to her children of their father‚Äôs death ‚Äúthe screaming and crying that followed haunt me to this day nothing has come close to the pain of this moment even now when my mind wanders back i shake and my throat constricts‚Äù she studied research on how to raise resilient children asked friends to make videos of themselves talking about their memories of goldberg filmed the children sharing their own memories of their father and played one of those films back to her daughter when she worried she was ‚Äúforgetting daddy because she has not seen him for so long‚Äù on what would have been his th birthday they wrote letters to him and sent them up in balloons she learned actively to seek out and treasure small moments of joy and made it a habit to write down a list of three moments at the end of every day ‚Äúwriting about joyful experiences for just three days can improve people‚Äôs moods and decrease their visits to health centres a full three months later‚Äù she reports in option b ‚Äì and having taken her advice and tried it i can confirm it works i almost winced with selfconsciousness making my first entry ‚Äì ‚Äúdancing with my son in a children‚Äôs nightclub‚Äù ‚Äì but it makes me smile every time i read it another device she learned works too to make a list each night of three things she‚Äôd done well that day in the early days hers were as modest as made tea got through all of my emails went to work and focused for most of one meeting ‚Äúbut it really does work‚Äù she says ‚Äúand everyone i know who‚Äôs tried it since then has told me it works it absolutely works‚Äù facebook twitter pinterest with mark zuckerberg photograph andrew gombertepa she could never have guessed that rebuilding selfconfidence would play such a big part in recovering from grief ‚Äúwell that part was so interesting for me right because i‚Äôd thought a lot about selfconfidence i wrote an entire book on selfconfidence the lean in community helps people get together to build selfconfidence now i had read about grief and i was not shocked by the anger not shocked by the sadness but the selfconfidence blow completely surprised me‚Äù confidence was not a commodity sandberg had ever been short of before now she felt like a failure both at work and at home ‚Äúi felt i could barely get through a meeting without thinking about dave and parenting is hard in the first place but i had a partner and i had two kids with very happy childhoods then all of a sudden i had two grieving children and no partner and no experience so my selfconfidence completely crumbled‚Äù what sandberg needed for the first time in her life was praise when she made mistakes in the early weeks back at work her colleagues would brush them off with ‚Äúhow could you keep things straight with all you‚Äôre going through‚Äù it was exactly what she had said herself in the past to anyone struggling with personal problems now she saw that far from making her feel better it only damaged her selfconfidence further she found out what actually helped when she panicked to zuckerberg about something she‚Äôd got wrong and he responded ‚Äúreally i thought you made a good point in that meeting and helped us make a better decision‚Äù empathy she writes ‚Äúwas nice but encouragement was better‚Äù another mistake she‚Äôd made before goldberg died was to ask people in trouble ‚Äúis there anything i can do‚Äù she says ‚Äúi really meant it but it kind of shifts the burden to the person who needs the help to tell you‚Äù the classic inquiry ‚Äúhow are you‚Äù also turned out to be unhelpful ‚Äúwell my husband just died on the floor of a gym like how am i‚Äù the more meaningful question she learned is ‚Äúhow are you today‚Äù mark is why i‚Äôm walking when i felt so isolated and just needed to cry i would drag him into his conference room but the biggest ‚Äì and remarkably common ‚Äì mistake is to ask nothing at all ‚Äúi want to talk about dave bringing up dave to me is always a positive it doesn‚Äôt make me sad i know he‚Äôs gone‚Äù i ask if anyone has said they didn‚Äôt like to mention him as they didn‚Äôt want to ‚Äúremind‚Äù her of her loss and she laughs ‚Äúyes it‚Äôs not possible to remind me‚Äù she recommends something she calls the platinum rule of friendship ‚Äúnot to treat people as you want to be treated but treat people as they want to be treated that‚Äôs a pretty big mind shift and some peo