erg‚Äôs sharing manifesto drives facebook  bloomberg how sheryl sandberg‚Äôs sharing manifesto drives facebook the coo inspires her fans and her employees to talk about sadness even tragedy at work that can be healing‚Äîand very good for business photographer¬†mark peterson for bloomberg businessweek by sarah frier sarahfrier more stories by sarah frier april    am edt on the last day in january about two dozen prolific users of facebook were invited to the social network‚Äôs headquarters in menlo park calif there they were arranged in a circle of brightly colored chairs to meet sheryl sandberg the company‚Äôs secondhighestranking executive and the oprah of corporate america the guests who had made lifechanging friendships using an organizational tool called facebook groups were invited to ask sandberg questions she insisted that she had to hear their stories firstthat‚Äôs when the tears started flowing a woman talked about how a facebook post on her struggle to become a mother led her to adopt a foster child two women from opposite coasts discussed how they‚Äôd become close by starting a private group to help women of color navigate mental health issues and a dallas waiter who‚Äôd lost his leg because of a rare bone disease talked about meeting a man who‚Äôd helped him raise money to try out for a soccer team for the disabled sandberg dressed in a loose white sweater jeans and boots california quietluxury style leaned in over and over to listen offering words of encouragement and hugs ‚Äúi love this‚Äù she told them after the sudden death of her husband david goldberg two years ago she was comforted to know that facebook was helping others cope with their own hardshipsas they talked cameras and boom mics followed members of the press looked on from the edge of the room the publicized event was in celebration of friends day a facebookconceived holiday with all the authenticity of greeting card company concoctions like ‚Äúgrandparents day‚Äù but really it was just another normal morning at facebook inc where employees are generally encouraged to share their personal challenges with colleagues nor would the event have been out of place in the emotionally welladjusted atmosphere that now characterizes many corporate cultures thanks in large part to sandberg herself on friends day mark zuckerberg facebook‚Äôs ceo also enthusiastically joined the festivities but when guests were asked for the highlight of the trip‚Äîdinner out in palo alto or the session where they got to give product advice‚Äîone woman quickly answered ‚Äúgetting a selfie with sheryl‚Äùsandberg‚Äôs message of openness and empathy may come across as a selfserving schtick facebook‚Äôs coo encouraging people to overshare is like exxon mobil promoting oil but since she‚Äôs one of the most powerful women in business you can‚Äôt just dismiss her as the chief emoting officer there‚Äôs what sandberg‚Äôs accomplished at zuckerberg‚Äôs side‚Äîthe company is with a market value of  billion the world‚Äôs fifthlargest and affects the daily lives of its almost  billion users there‚Äôs also her hardertoquantify role as this decade‚Äôs leading culture shifter in the long slog toward a corporate reality in which winning doesn‚Äôt require posing as a mandecades ago pioneering feminists like betty friedan and gloria steinem pointed out that compartmentalizing domestic and professional spheres was a way for men to stay in charge because women can‚Äôt hide the fact that they‚Äôre pregnant or breastfeeding simply being female looked unprofessional and as long as problems related to child care and other forms of domestic labor‚Äîtraditionally the purview of women‚Äîweren‚Äôt seen as work public policies would never change and women would never become part of political decisionmakingthe foremothers of today‚Äôs female ceos organized women to become a vocal force asserting that their issues were collective ones but over the years the pace of change slowed sandberg in her blockbuster bestseller lean in women work and the will to lead cowritten by nell scovell and through her nonprofit leaninorg picked up the thread encouraging women to get together online and in person to share the struggles and feelings involved in bridging those stillpresent divides sandberg‚Äôs central management message was a compelling one ‚Äúbring your whole self into work‚Äù she‚Äôd conveyed this inspirational koan in a commencement address to harvard business school her alma mater in  the year before the book was published the slightly paradoxical idea was for women to drop their professional facades and convey vulnerability to better connect with colleagues and customers while at the same time acting with the confidence needed to rise in the workplacenow with the publication of a new instructional memoir option b facing adversity building resilience and finding joy sandberg has taken that cause even further moving workday anguish over setbacks such as divorce disease and death from solo crying jags in the office parking lot to company hallways conference rooms and boardrooms after sandberg became a widow and the single mother of a gradeschoolage son and daughter she was vulnerable in a way she couldn‚Äôt control ‚Äúif i believed before dave died in bringing your whole self to work what i learned after option b is you have no choice‚Äù she says during an interview at facebook ‚Äúwhen your whole self is going through adversity and tragedy that whole self comes to work‚Äùin the book cowritten with wharton school professor and ted talk superstar adam grant she weaves her family‚Äôs story of loss with academic data on recovery from tragedy and with anecdotes from others facing cancer disability or mental illness the title refers to a conversation sandberg had with her friend phil deutch a managing partner at an energy fund as she recounts in the first chapter called ‚Äúbreathing again‚Äù he offered to fill in for goldberg at a fatherchild school activity ‚Äúbut i want dave‚Äù sandberg writes deutch put his arm around her and said ‚Äúoption a is not available so let‚Äôs kick the shit out of option b‚Äù back at work motivational posters encouraging people to ‚Äúkick the shit out of option b‚Äù went up all over the sprawling campustwo friends gave sandberg chains on which to string her husband‚Äôs wedding ring she melded them and wears the necklace dailyphotographer¬†mark peterson¬†for bloomberg businessweeksandberg doesn‚Äôt have an office in the den of transparency that is facebook but she does have a personal conference room a glasswalled case with a table right in the middle of all the standing desks and modernist furniture on a recent tuesday between meetings she uses a spare moment as many workers do checking for comments on her most recent facebook post an announcement of the upcoming book unlike most people she has thousands to wade throughone comment jumps out at her from a woman who says her husband died a week after goldberg passed away ‚Äúshe went back to work after  days because i did‚Äù sandberg says folding her hands over her chest while seated in her conference room ‚Äúi would never want anyone to lose their husband at  ever but given that it happened isn‚Äôt it incredible that i feel connected to her after the post this morning i feel less alone‚Äùsandberg exudes such intense sincerity when she talks that it can come across as manufactured her eyes fix on listeners as she takes them through data a vignette and a handy concluding sentence‚Äîexactly the package they need to convey it to someone else her tone is one you‚Äôd use talking to a close girlfriend though her sentences end with her voice falling which underscores the seriousness of what she‚Äôs saying her conversations incorporate calculated pauses that provide opportunities to absorb her message she‚Äôs disciplined too even when she‚Äôs telling recycled stories and jokes friends and colleagues who‚Äôve heard them before marvel that she can deliver them with fresh emotion and impactsandberg contends that she‚Äôs almost an accidental prophet of openness in the workplace a decade ago as an executive at google inc she always worked from  am to  pm then her first child was born and she found she couldn‚Äôt stand coming home to find him already asleep she started sneaking out of the office early sometimes placing a decoy jacket on her chair leaving the light on at her desk or scheduling afternoon meetings in other buildings so her colleagues wouldn‚Äôt see her leave the subterfuge continued for years then in  about a month before facebook‚Äôs initial public offering she admitted to a reporter that she regularly left work at  the revelation blared across multiple news outlets sandberg was worried that she would be lectured or fired instead her brazenness was heralded by other female professionals the women of the legal team at yahoo inc sent her flowers with a card saying that they too were leaving at  ‚Äúi didn‚Äôt realize how much noise there would be‚Äù sandberg says ‚Äúa friend told me ‚Äòyou couldn‚Äôt have gotten more publicity if you murdered someone with an ax‚Äô‚Äâ‚Äù this was in the innocent days before facebook live the streaming video service was used by murderers for prwhen she submitted the lean in manuscript to editors later that year they told her that the first draft was boring it was all data and research with nothing about her own challenges navigating the workplace obstacle course of gender expectations and entrenched sexism goldberg told her nobody would read it if she didn‚Äôt put herself into it she began rewriting sandberg says she didn‚Äôt want to overshare but apparently the market was demanding itwhen goldberg died she regretted the fame the book had brought her ‚Äúif i could have gone back and rewritten lean in i would have because i didn‚Äôt want to live publicly‚Äù she says ‚Äúbut then it was so isolating‚Äù people avoided her gaze interactions became stilted she confided to zuckerberg that she felt as though her workplace friendships were melting away one night before bed she wrote a word explanation of what she was going through and how she hoped people would interact with her it started as a cathartic exercise she didn‚Äôt think she would publish it but when she woke up she changed her mind and put it on facebook in lean in sandberg had admitted to crying at work another confession the media jumped on but this was the first time she‚Äôd shared anything so deeply personal the post received  comments many from coworkers acknowledging her struggleof course one could argue that sandberg had begun down this path the moment she joined facebook‚Äîa company that earns billions from getting people to open up about their lives she and zuckerberg have frequently been asked to lead by example when facebook lifted a tactic from twitter and gave public figures the option of opening their profiles to people who weren‚Äôt friends but followers ‚Äúi wasn‚Äôt going to do it and neither was mark‚Äù sandberg says then a communications executive caryn marooney told them they would have to do it if they wanted others to fall in line ‚Äúi think the product has really changed us‚Äù sandberg says earnestly zuckerberg gives her a lot of credit too ‚Äúwhen sheryl first came to facebook she started a tradition of checkingin to our leadership meetings‚Äù he wrote in an email ‚Äúcheckingin‚Äù means each person around the table is invited to discuss their current emotional and professional state before they get down to business ‚Äúnine years later we‚Äôre still doing it‚Äùin  sandberg hosted an allhands meeting to talk about the connection between sharing personal stories and working at a place like facebook she talked at length about the company‚Äôs culture and how employees were individually charged with serving its mission ‚Äúto make the world more open and connected‚Äù then she introduced some employees whom she now describes as ‚Äúa bunch of people who went onstage and shared a lot of really personal stuff things they‚Äôd gone through and how facebook connected to it‚Äùone employee who got the message was stephanie latham a marketing director who coordinates facebook‚Äôs relationship with the auto industry and had just relocated to menlo park when she found out she had cancer and was pregnant reluctant to post about her personal life she told only her team so they could prepare for her unpredictable schedule soon after a group of her coworkers including some she didn‚Äôt know produced a video for her set to pharrell williams‚Äôs happy latham was moved to tearsnews of the video reached sandberg who encouraged latham to share her story at facebook‚Äôs internal women‚Äôs leadership day conference ‚Äúthat was way out of my comfort zone but i felt like it was a necessary thing to do‚Äù latham says in an interviewthe episode sounds like a scene from the circle the bestselling thriller by dave eggers that‚Äôs just been released as a feature film starring emma watson in it employees at a facebooklike company are svengalied into making their lives and emotions transparent as a precursor to totalitarian thought control but in real life latham‚Äôs story didn‚Äôt end in treachery and murder it just went viral on the company‚Äôs internal network responses from colleagues were accompanied by the hashtag fbfamily which was later printed on blue rubber wristbands and passed around campus latham now cancerfree with a healthy daughter credits sandberg for helping her find a supportive community at work ‚Äúshe leads so strongly by example‚Äù latham saysample sharing among colleagues is inculcated in employees from the second they walk in the door new hires are invited by the hr department to a facebook group of their peers and are expected to befriend one another and members of their future teams collaboration among all employees occurs on facebook groups milestones and failures are publicized on the network as well as ‚Äúfaceversaries‚Äù‚Äîanniversaries of workers‚Äô start dates these are hallowed events acknowledged like birthdays with hundreds of celebratory posts from colleagues and a note from the employee reflecting on what he or she has learned while tagging the bosses and coworkers who made it all possible‚Äúafter the post this morning i feel less alone‚Äùmany workers find the approach freeing in february  an engineering director named david ferguson posted to the global facebook employee network an explanation of why the following monday she would arrive as a woman and go by the name deb in september oscar perez a diversity director who posts about life as a gay latino shared thoughts about the day his father became a us citizen ‚Äúyou think it would waste time to sit around and talk about your life but it doesn‚Äôt‚Äù says sandberg ‚Äúit actually saves time because it‚Äôs so present for people that having an opportunity to talk about it actually¬†helps‚Äùfacebook celebrates the values of transparency and personal sharing with the exuberance of a company that knows it might be very good for business but the sandberg effect is now showing up at places that don‚Äôt capitalize on the human urge to communicate mary barra the ceo of general motors co posts on facebook about issues such as female empowerment another close sandberg friend walmart stores inc ceo doug mcmillon responds to customer complaints on the social network with his personal email address this year he became the first chief executive to be featured in one of the retail giant‚Äôs commercials ‚Äúthe reason i share i‚Äôm proud of the people i work with‚Äùit‚Äôs sandberginspired postmodern marketing‚Äîa corporate attempt to strengthen bonds with customers via an abundance of sharing that in a prior era might have seemed unbecoming ‚Äúit makes us trust them more or at a minimum know them more and that‚Äôs good for loyalty over time‚Äù says mike hoefflinger a former facebook employee who wrote a book about the social network‚Äúthis younger generation really craves this authenticity this vulnerability‚Äù explains kellie mcelhaney a professor at the university of california at berkeley‚Äôs haas school of business she sees sandberg as far ahead of the game ‚Äúwhen i hang out with these most powerful women particularly in tech they‚Äôre just like machines‚Äù she says recounting a time she overheard two female executives compare recent results of blood tests to measure their testosterone levels among the regular churn of leadership books a more recent set has emerged promising to teach authenticity and touting research showing that those in¬†upper management who master it will have more swaysandberg employs this soft power even in her conversations with wall street before facebook‚Äôs earnings reports are published her team helps her gather compelling anecdotes from advertisers that take advantage of the company‚Äôs usertargeting tools she keeps the stories in a list beside her to use as examples on the investor call that accompanies the quarterly release ‚Äúi‚Äôm doing that on purpose on earnings calls and in all my communication because stories are what help us understand things‚Äù she saysin facebook‚Äôs frank gehrydesigned building  sandberg posts openly about her life and asks colleagues to bring their ‚Äúwhole self‚Äù to workphotographer¬†mark peterson¬†for bloomberg businessweekif the company‚Äôs new product workplace succeeds sandbergian management will have proven to be scalable various silicon valley startups have tried to create versions of facebook for work slack technology inc the creator of a popular office messaging service is now valued at  billion facebook‚Äôs answer provides an officefriendly version of its standard news feed‚Äîand a justification for employees to spend even more time on the network early adopters include starbucks viacom and the government of singaporethe attention sandberg‚Äôs book is getting comes at a good time for facebook the company has arrived at a moment when it desperately needs to be h